Graham Linehan, once celebrated for Father Ted and The IT Crowd, is now arrested at Heathrow over past posts on transgender issues. Whatever you think of his stance, the spectacle of armed police detaining a comedy writer for words should chill us all. When jokes become crimes and “incitement” is stretched to cover opinions, the law is no longer protecting people — it’s controlling them. Free speech in Britain is fading into prohibition, and that ought to trouble anyone who values liberty.

I sit down with Tommy Robinson for a frank, uncomfortable, necessary conversation about migration, identity, and who holds power in Britain. I push for unity over hate, local control over distant elites, and a Christian ethic of love—while acknowledging the anger, crimes, and failures that fuel today’s backlash. We challenge media and judicial narratives, test each other’s assumptions, and ask whether working-class Brits, Muslims, Sikhs and everyone in between can build cohesion without surrendering free speech or
